<s docid="SJMN91-06162032" num="7" wdcount="38"> The decision to evacuate one of the 
largest overseas U.S. military bases was made early today after searing gases, 
ash and rock shot out of 4,795-foot Mount Pinatubo on Sunday at speeds of up to 
60 mph .</s>

<s docid="SJMN91-06162032" num="10" wdcount="20"> The volcano, about 10 miles west of 
the air base, came to life last week after six centuries of dormancy.</s>

<s docid="SJMN91-06162032" num="12" wdcount="27"> Gases, ash and molten rock continued 
to pour out of the mountain today, enshrouding it in thick, gray clouds of ash 
and steam that rose 12,000 feet.</s>

<s docid="SJMN91-06162032" num="30" wdcount="29"> Areas around the 4,452-foot volcano 
covered by evacuation warnings were expanded to protect people against possible 
slides of volcanic debris that could be triggered by the rain, police said.</s>
 
<s docid="SJMN91-06162032" num="41" wdcount="18"> Mount Pinatubo, which last had a 
major eruption in 1n 1380, began to show signs of activity in April.</s> 

<s docid="SJMN91-06165048" num="7" wdcount="37"> Three major new eruptions rocked 
Mount Pinatubo late Wednesday night and early today, forcing another emergency 
evacuation of Clark Air Base and increasing fears of even more violent 
explosions from the long-dormant volcano in the days ahead.</s>

<s docid="SJMN91-06164210" num="46" wdcount="27"> The Americans who fled Clark with a 
few belongings Monday moved in with sailors and their families at Subic Bay 
naval base, 50 miles to the southwest.</s>

<s docid="SJMN91-06167046" num="13" wdcount="45"> The U.S. military began flying home 
hundreds of the 28,000 Americans who crowded onto Subic Bay Naval Base as a 
bizarre tropical blizzard of thick volcanic ash caused power failures across the 
base Friday during a third day of increasingly violent eruptions of Mount 
Pinatubo.</s>

<s docid="SJMN91-06167046" num="16" wdcount="30"> At least four people have died, 24 
